ce:section.ce:para:
Under the selected conditions, the reaction of FR-Au3+ to form AuNPs is slow. When CD is added, it can obviously catalyze the reaction to generate more AuNPs. When Apt is added, it is adsorbed on the surface of CD due to the electrostatic effect, which weaken the catalytic effect of CD and reduces the AuNPs generated in the system. In the analytical system, when As+3/Pb2+/Hg2+ is added reaspectively, Apt specifically combines with As+3/Pb2+/Hg2+, which leads to the release of carbon dots and promote FR-Au3+ reaction to generate AuNPs (Fig. 4
                        ). The SERS spectra of the AptAs-As+3-C60/CDAu/CDAg/CDN-FR-HAuCl4-VBB system (Figs. 4a, S4a–c) and Apt-Hg2+/Pb2+-CDAu-FR-HAuCl4-VBB system (Fig. 4b–c) were recorded, and the analysis system generates SERS characteristic peaks at 251 cm−1, 445 cm−1, 805 cm−1, 1192 cm−1, 1386 cm−1 and 1619 cm−1. With the increase of the target ion, the SERS signal gradually increases linearly. Among them, the change of SERS signal of I1619 cm
                        −1 is the most obvious, and the linearity is good. Therefore, the intensity of change at 1619 cm−1 was used for the SERS detection of As+3. The RRS and Abs spectra were also recorded. With the increase of As+3 concentration, more AuNPs are generated in the system, and the RRS signal gradually increases. For the Apt-As+3-CDAu-FR/glucose/ethanol/glycerol-HAuCl4 systems (Figs. 4d, S5a–c), they generate two RRS peaks at 370 and 540 nm. The RRS signal change at 370 nm is more sensitive than that at 540 nm, so we chose 370 nm as the characteristic peak for RRS detecting As+3. The AptAs-As+3-CDAu-FR/glucose/glycerol/ethanol-HAuCl4 system also produces a strong Abs peak around 310 nm (Figs. 4e, S6a–c), the peak absorption signal is indirectly enhanced with the analyte concentration increasing, and the peak is gradually increased (Figs. 4e, S6a–c). For the Apt-As+3-CDAu-FR/ethanol-HAuCl4 systems, there is an absorption peak at 550/580 nm (Figs. 4e, S6b). For the glycerol-HAuCl4 system (Fig. S6a), an absorption peak is generated at 310 nm, but there is no obvious absorption peak at about 500 nm. For the glucose-HAuCl4 system, in addition to the absorption peak at 550 nm, a stronger absorption peak also appears at 310 nm (Fig. S6c). In short, the Apt- CDAu-FR-HAuCl4 system can be used to determine As+3 spectrophotometrically.
